Question 1¶

Tabular data contains different types of variables. Some variables are categorical and some are numerical and continuous. Write a short note on the different types of variables. Include appropriate examples in your description

Types of variables¶

Variables are mainly of two types categorical(qualitative) and numeric(quantitative). Let's discuss them.

Categorical Variables¶

  • Categorical Variable are variables which only take a finite number of values.

  • These values need not have to be numbers. For example, consider a database which contains all information of the students of IITG. Let Programme be the variable which tells us whether a student is in B.Tech, or M.Tech, or Ph.D or M.Sc, etc. The variable Programme is a categorical variable.

  • Categorical variables divide the data into several groups or categories. For example, the data of students at IITG can be divided into several categories such as B.Tech students, M.Tech students, etc.

  • Categorical variables can further be categorized as follows :

    • Nominal: These are variables that have two or more categories, but the categories do not have an intrinsic order between them.
      • Example : The Programme variable discussed above was a Nominal variable
    • Binary/Dichotomous: These variables are nominal variables which have only two categories.
      • Example : Let sex be the variable which tells us a particular student is Male or Female. Then sex is a binary variable.

    • Oridnal: These are variables that have two or more categories just like nominal variables but the categories here can be ordered or ranked.

      • Example: Suppose that in out student dataset we want to classify students base on their academics, where the categories are

        • Poor(less than 4 CGPA)
        • Below Average(4 to 6 CGPA)
        • Average(6 to 7.5 CGPA)
        • Above Average (7.5 to 8.5 CGPA)

        • Good(8.5 to 10 CGPA).

          Then the variable which will store this information will be a ordinal variable. Because here the categories can be ranked as Poor < Below Average < Average < Above Average < Good.

Numeric Variables: These are variables whose values are numbers (except numbers which are codes standing up for categories).¶

  • Numerical variables are mainly of two types, conitnuous variable and discrete variable which takes continuous and discrete values respectively.

  • These variables are very important in statistics. In categorical variables, the categories describe the variables but in numerical variable, we can find average,median,standard deviation, etc. of and these quantities are used to describe the variable.

  • Let's discuss type of numeric variables.

    • Discrete Variables :
      • A discrete variable is a numerical variable with a fintie/countable number of possible values.
      • Example : The number of courses a student takes in a semester is discrete variable. The student can take 4 or 5 or 6 or more number of courses. Number of courses for a student will always be a proper subset of the natural numbers, so the variable takes only finite values.

    • Continuous Variable :

      • A continuous variable is a variable which can take any value in a continuous/interval range.
      • Example : Weight(in KG) of all students at IITG is a continous variable. The weight of a student can be any positive real number between 0 to infinity(If we don't know beforehand what is the minimum and maximum weight, then the range of the variable is hard to predict).

Question 2¶

Tabular data are often presented in one of the following two formats: wide format, and long format. Write a short note differentiating the two formats. Your note should include appropriate examples. Further, using your choice of tool and language, show how you can convert one format into another.

Wide format tabular data :¶

  • In the wide format tabular data each record is stored in a single row and each variable/atttribute is stored in a separate column.
  • Thus the total number of columns of a wide format tabular data is atleast equal to the total number of variables.

  • Example of wide format :

    |Roll number | Programme | First Name | Last Name | Year | |:----------:|:--------:|:--------:|:--------:|:-----:| | 224161018 | M.Tech | Mohit | Sharma | First | | 224161019 | M.Tech | Neel | Mani | First | | 224161020 | M.Tech | Nikhil | Thoshar | First | | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |

  • Wide format is heavily used in data analysis. It is easier to find the mean, variance, etc of numerical variables if the variable is stored in a column. Wide format is also easy to interpret

Long format tabular data :¶

  • In the long format tabular data each record is stored in multiple rows,where each row has same identifier/primary key/index and one variable.
  • Thus number of rows required to store each record in the long format tabular data is atleast equal to the total number of variables. So the total number of rows in this type of arrangement is going to be high.
  • Example of long format:
    |Roll Number | Variable| Value | |:------------|:---------:|-------:| | 224161018 | Programme | M.Tech | | 224161018 | First Name | Mohit | | 224161018 | Last Name | Sharma | | 224161018 | Year |First | | 224161019 | Programme | M.Tech | | 224161019 | First Name | Neel | | 224161019 | Last Name | Mani | | 224161019 | Year |First | | 224161020 | Programme | M.Tech | | 224161020 | First Name | Nikhil | | 224161020 | Last Name | Thoshar | | 224161020 | Year |First | | ... | ... | ... |
  • Some softwares require us to use long format when we try to visualize multiple variables in a single plot.

Converting one format into another in pyhton :¶

(I)¶

Which graph you will use to plot data for gender distribution and height distribution? Plot and Justify. Do we need any plot to understand gender distribution?

Plot for gender distribution¶

The plot that suits the best to visualize the distribution of a categorical variable are bar plot. We use bar plot here. In bar plot, the categories are in one axis and in the other axis the frequencies of the categories are plotted as tall buildings(called bar), the higher the frequency of one category, the taller its building. By comparing the height of the buildings, we can easily interpret which categories are have high frequency.

Since here we have only two values for the categorical variable 'sex', so the number of bars are going to be two, which well enable us to understand the distribution quickly.

Another plot which can be used to visualize the distribution of a categorical variable is pie chart or circle chart. The frequency of a level of a categorical variable can be interpreted as a portion of the area of the circle.

In [89]:
sex_dist=heights['sex'].value_counts().to_frame()
sex_dist['sex']=sex_dist['sex']/heights.shape[0] # Normalizing the frequencies

plt.xlabel('Sex')
plt.ylabel('Frequency Count')

Plot for height distribution¶

A Histogram is a good plot for visualizing the distribution of a continuous variable. In a histogram, we divide the x-axis into several intervals(called bins),then we count the number of values that fall in each bin and plot these values as bars on top of the intervals. This quicly tells us where majority of our data lies, what is the range of our data.

Plotting normalized frequency distribution of heights¶

In [90]:
heights_col=heights['height']
total_obs=len(heights_col)
# Calculating Normalized Frequency Distribution
min_h=heights_col.min()
max_h=heights_col.max()
n=10
b_s=(max_h-min_h)/n
H=np.zeros(n)
for i in range(total_obs):
  b_i=int(np.floor((heights_col[i]-min_h)/(b_s)))
  if b_i==n:
    b_i=b_i-1
  H[b_i]=H[b_i]+1/total_obs

bin_arr=[min_h+b_s*i for i in range(n+1)]
bin_arr=np.array(bin_arr)
plt.bar(bin_arr[:-1],H,width=b_s,align='edge')
Out[90]:
<BarContainer object of 10 artists>

Histogram, which shows the normalized frequency distribution of the heights, is a good plot to see what range of height contains 95% of the data. We can quicky see which bins have very less frequency on top of it and the remaining bins are the bins where our majority of our data goes.

Use smoothed density curve to plot the height of Male students, highlighting the students with heights between 66 and 72 inches. For the same data, plot and justify how is smoothed density graph different from the histogram.

Plotting the height of Male students using Smoohted density curve and highlighting the students with heights between 66 and 72 inches.

In [96]:
sns.kdeplot(data=male_height_data)
ax=sns.kdeplot(data=male_height_data)

kde_lines = ax.get_lines()[-1]
kde_x, kde_y = kde_lines.get_data()

mask=(kde_x > 66) & (kde_x < 72) 
filled_x, filled_y = kde_x[mask], kde_y[mask]

ax.fill_between(filled_x, filled_y)
ax.set_xlabel('Height(in inches)')
ax.set_title('Distribution of Height(66-72 is shaded)')

For the same data, plot and justify how is smoothed density graph different from the histogram.

In [118]:
fig,axes=plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,5))
sns.histplot(ax=axes[0],data=male_height_data,bins=20)
axes[0].set_title("Histogram of Height")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Height(in inches)")

sns.kdeplot(ax=axes[1],data=male_height_data,fill=True)
axes[1].set_title("Density plot of Height")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Height(in inches)")
Out[118]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Height(in inches)')
  • The y-labels in density plot are changed from count to densities. Area under the curve for any interval gives an approximation to the proportion of heights in that interval.
  • In histogram we can see few local peaks(in between 60 and 65, in between 76 to 80), and in the density plot these peaks are not there.
  • Smooth density plot helps us to visualize the transition between heights smoothly(continuously), but in histogram the transition occurs in jumps/steps.

Which plot will we use to understand the correlation of palmitic acid with other acids?¶

To understand the correlation between two continuous variables, scatterplot is the best choice. If X and Y are two continuous variables, then scatterplot plots different values that X and Y take on the plane.

If there is some relationship between X and Y the scatterplot will probably capture the relationship by showing us some patterns in the plot.

Let's plot the scatterplot of palmitic acid with few other acids

In [52]:
fig,axes=plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(10,10),sharey=True)
sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[0,0],x=olive.palmitoleic,y=olive.palmitic)
axes[0,0].set_title("Palmitoleic vs Palmitic")

sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[0,1],data=olive,x='stearic',y='palmitic')
axes[0,1].set_title('Stearic vs Palmitic')

sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[1,0],data=olive,x='linoleic',y='palmitic')
axes[1,0].set_title('Linoleic vs Palmitic')

sns.scatterplot(ax=axes[1,1],data=olive,x='oleic',y='palmitic')
axes[1,1].set_title('Oleic vs Palmitic')

fig.suptitle("Palmitic Acid vs Other Acids")
Out[52]:
Text(0.5, 0.98, 'Palmitic Acid vs Other Acids')

By seeing the above plot, one can quickly understand the correlation of palmitic acids with palmitoleic, stearic, linoleic, and oleic.

  • Palmitic and Palmitoleic acids are positively correlated.
  • Palmitic and Stearica acids are negatively correlated.
  • Palmitic and Linoleic acids are positively correlated.
  • Palmitic and Oleic acids are negatively correlated.

We can get more insights on the correlation using scatterplots. For example, Does 'region' plays any role in the correlation of palmitic acid with other acids varies from region to region ? Let's see this

Surely we have more insights now as compared to before.

  • Palmitic vs Palmitoleic:
    • There is almost no correlation between the two acids in Sardinia and Northern Italy regions.
    • Only in the Southern Italy region the two variables are positively correlated.
  • Palmitic vs Stearic:
    • Again there is almost no correlation between the two acids in Sardinia and Northern Italy regions.
    • The acids are negatively correlated in the Southern Italy region.
  • Palmitic vs Linoleic:
    • There is positive correlation between the two acids in the Southern Italy region.
    • There is weak negative correlation between the two acids in the Northern Italy region.
    • There is no correlation between the two acids in the Sardinia region
  • Palmitic vs Oleic:
    • There is negative correlation in all the regions.
